# Argo CD git auth — the GitHub App, installed per org

Argo CD authenticates to GitHub with a **GitHub App**, never a PAT (invariant 4).
The reality that bites people: **one App, installed separately on every org**
whose repos Argo CD must read (the infra repo, plus every app repo on the
blessed path and every repo a PR-preview ApplicationSet watches). Each install
has its own **installation ID**; Argo CD needs **one credential per org** (same
private key, that org's installation ID). These are **infrastructure
credentials**: created directly in the cluster, **never committed, not even
sealed** (invariant 3).

PUBLIC repos need none of this — Argo CD reads them anonymously (a token only
raises the GitHub API rate limit for the PR-preview generator). Set this up when
a repo is private.

## The App (once per instance)

Create **one** GitHub App for the whole instance, named `Server
{{ community_name }}` (or `Server <org>`):

- **Permissions:** Repository → Contents: **Read-only** (Argo CD only reads).
  For PR previews also grant **Pull requests: Read-only** (the PullRequest
  generator lists open PRs).
- **Where can this App be installed:** Any account (so it can be installed on
  every org that hosts repos Argo CD reads).
- Note the **App ID** and generate a **private key** (`.pem`). The key is
  shared across every installation.

## Install on each org

Install the App on **every** org whose repos Argo CD reads — this repo's org
(`{{ github_owner }}`) and any org hosting an app overlay or a previewed repo.
Each installation gets a distinct installation ID.

Find an org's installation ID (App ID is the same everywhere):

```bash
gh api /orgs/<org>/installations \
  --jq '.installations[] | select(.app_id==<app-id>) | .id'
```

For a user account rather than an org, use `/users/<user>/installation`:

```bash
gh api /users/<user>/installation --jq '.id'
```

## One Argo CD credential per org (in the cluster, never in git)

Argo CD reads git credentials from Secrets in the `argocd` namespace labeled
`argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type`. Use a **`repo-creds`** entry keyed by the
org's URL prefix — it then covers every repo under that org:

```bash
kubectl create secret generic <org>-argocd-secret -n argocd \
  --from-literal=type=git \
  --from-literal=url=https://github.com/<org> \
  --from-literal=githubAppID=<app-id> \
  --from-literal=githubAppInstallationID=<installation-id> \
  --from-file=githubAppPrivateKey=<app-key.pem>
kubectl label secret <org>-argocd-secret -n argocd \
  argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type=repo-creds
```

Do this for `{{ github_owner }}` (this repo's org) and once more for every other
org Argo CD reads — same `<app-id>` and same `.pem`, only the installation ID
differs. The root `Application` and all child `Application`s whose `repoURL`
starts with `https://github.com/<org>` then authenticate automatically.

## PR-preview generator token

The PullRequest generator in a preview `ApplicationSet`
(`patterns/app-preview-prs/`) authenticates with the **same** App. Point its
`tokenRef` at the org's secret:

```yaml
generators:
  - pullRequest:
      github:
        owner: <org>
        repo: <app>
        tokenRef:
          secretName: <org>-argocd-secret
          key: githubAppPrivateKey
```

## Verify

```bash
# Sources resolve (no "authentication required"):
argocd repo list                         # or, without the CLI:
kubectl -n argocd get application root -o jsonpath='{.status.sync.status}{"\n"}'
kubectl -n argocd get applications       # all Synced/Healthy, none "ComparisonError"
```

## Rebuild note (accepted trade-off)

Because these credentials are never in git (invariant 3), they are **not**
reproducible from the repo. On a cluster rebuild, recreate every
`<org>-argocd-secret` by hand with the commands above (App ID + per-org
installation ID + the shared `.pem`). Keep the `.pem` and App ID in the
operator's password manager, not in this repo.
